   {en:"\"It is a truth universally acknowledged, that a single man in possession of a good fortune, must be in want of a wife.\" — VERBAL IRONY + MOCK-SOLEMN TONE: 과학 법칙의 문체로 쓰인 동네의 욕망.", ko:"서술 목소리·아이러니·결혼관 문제 전부에 꽂히는 만능 인용"},
   {en:"\"...he is considered as the rightful property of some one or other of their daughters.\" — DICTION: 'property'(재산) 한 단어가 결혼 시장의 본질을 자백한다.", ko:"결혼=거래 주제용. 남자가 '재산'으로 사물화되는 역전도 짚을 것"},
   {en:"\"The business of her life was to get her daughters married.\" — DICTION: Mrs. Bennet의 인생이 'business'로 정의됨 — 모성의 언어가 아니라 직업의 언어.", ko:"Mrs. Bennet을 옹호적으로 재독해할 때(entail 맥락) 근거로"}
  ],
  q:"'universally acknowledged'를 'widely believed'로 바꾸면 무엇이 사라지는가? 두 표현의 격차를 한 단락으로.",
  models:[
   {lens:"word",
    p:"The phrase \"universally acknowledged\" — rather than the humbler \"widely believed\" — does the sentence's heaviest work.",
    e:"Austen opens with \"a truth universally acknowledged\" about wealthy single men.",
    t:"This is hyperbole wearing the costume of scientific diction.",
    a:"\"Universally\" claims the status of a natural law for what is, in fact, the wishful thinking of a few country mothers; the grander the claim, the smaller its real owner looks. Swap in \"widely believed\" and the joke dies, because belief admits doubt while \"acknowledged\" pretends the arguing is already over. The inflation is the irony.",
    l:"One adjective thus sets the novel's method: solemn language, placed where it does not belong, becomes a scalpel.",
    ko:"단어 렌즈의 정석 — '더 평범한 대안과 비교'(rather than the blander...) 구문이 분석을 자동으로 굴려준다."},
   {lens:"narrator",
    p:"The mock-solemn narrative voice treats local gossip as cosmic law, and the gap between manner and matter is where Austen lives.",
    e:"A \"truth universally acknowledged\" turns out, within two pages, to be merely \"the minds of the surrounding families\".",
    t:"The technique is free indirect discourse: the narrator borrows the neighbourhood's voice without quotation marks.",
    a:"Because no one is officially speaking, no one can be officially blamed — the mockery is deniable, which makes it sharper. The reader is flattered into collusion: we hear the pomposity, smile, and have already taken the narrator's side before a single character appears.",
    l:"The opening therefore announces not a theme but a relationship — narrator and reader, allied above the heads of Meryton.",
    ko:"서술 렌즈: '따옴표 없는 빌린 목소리'라는 한 줄 정의를 박고, 효과를 '독자와의 공모'로 끌고 가는 동선."}
  ],
  drill:"같은 문장을 reader 렌즈로: 'The reader is positioned to ...'로 시작하는 P 한 문장만 써보기."},

 {id:"s2", sp:3, t:"\"Tolerable\" — 공개 처형된 자존심", ch:"Ch.3",
  set:"Meryton 무도회. Darcy가 Elizabeth를 두고, 그녀가 들을 수 있는 거리에서 말한다.",
  quotes:[
   {en:"\"She is tolerable; but not handsome enough to tempt me.\" — DICTION: 'tolerable'(견딜 만한)은 칭찬의 최저 등급 — 평가 자체가 모욕인 단어.", ko:"prejudice의 '근거 있는 출발점' 논증의 핵심 증거"},
   {en:"\"...I am in no humour at present to give consequence to young ladies who are slighted by other men.\" — CLASS LOGIC: 남이 거른 것은 나도 거른다 — 사람을 시장의 재고로 보는 문장.", ko:"Darcy의 pride를 '개인 성격'이 아니라 '계급 논리'로 분석할 때"},
   {en:"Elizabeth \"told the story, however, with great spirit among her friends.\" — CHARACTERIZATION: 모욕을 농담으로 변환하는 방어 기제 — 하지만 잊지는 않는다.", ko:"Elizabeth의 wit가 '상처의 가공품'임을 보이는 디테일"}
  ],
  q:"무도회 예법(배경지식 카드 참조)을 근거로, 이 발언이 '사적인 평가'가 아니라 '공개적 행위'임을 논증해보기.",
  models:[
   {lens:"word",
    p:"\"Tolerable\" wounds more efficiently than open rudeness could.",
    e:"Darcy rates Elizabeth \"tolerable; but not handsome enough to tempt me\".",
    t:"The diction works by faint praise: the word concedes just enough to make its coldness deliberate.",
    a:"An insult can be dismissed as bad temper, but a measured assessment implies a careful look followed by a verdict — Elizabeth has been examined and priced. The market metaphor continues in \"tempt\", as though she were goods insufficiently discounted. Spoken within her hearing, under ballroom rules in which not being asked to dance is already a public grade, the sentence is less a remark than a posting of results.",
    l:"Austen thus gives Elizabeth's prejudice an honest receipt: it begins not in vanity but in evidence.",
    ko:"'모욕보다 평가가 더 아프다'는 역설을 A에서 길게 굴리는 게 포인트. 배경지식(무도회 규칙)이 분석을 한 단계 올려준다."}
  ],
  drill:"dialogue 렌즈로: Darcy의 이 발언을 '듣는 사람'이 아니라 '말하는 사람'을 폭로하는 증거로 뒤집는 P 한 문장."},

 {id:"s3", sp:19, t:"Collins의 청혼 — 번호 매겨진 사랑", ch:"Ch.19",
  set:"사랑 고백의 형식으로 작성된 사업 보고서. 풍자의 교과서 장면.",
  quotes:[
   {en:"\"My reasons for marrying are, first ... secondly ... thirdly ...\" — STRUCTURE AS SATIRE: 고백의 자리에서 작동하는 보고서 형식 — 형식과 내용의 격차가 곧 코미디.", ko:"풍자·결혼관·희극 문제의 1순위 인용"},
   {en:"\"...it is the particular advice and recommendation of the very noble lady whom I have the honour of calling patroness.\" — SELF-EXPOSURE: 청혼 사유 3위가 '상사의 지시' — 신부보다 후원자가 높은 서열표.", ko:"Collins의 굴종(servility)과 권위 숭배 분석용"},
   {en:"\"I am therefore by no means discouraged by what you have just said.\" — DRAMATIC IRONY: 거절을 거절로 듣지 못하는 남자 — 여성의 'No'가 화폐가치를 갖지 못하던 시대의 풍자.", ko:"여성의 발언권 주제로 확장할 때. Elizabeth의 분노의 정당성 근거"},
   {en:"\"...your portion is unhappily so small that it will in all likelihood undo the effects of your loveliness.\" — ECONOMIC DICTION: 지참금이 매력을 '상쇄(undo)'한다 — 회계 언어로 쓰인 구애.", ko:"결혼=거래 주제. 'undo'라는 동사 하나를 저울에 올릴 것"}
  ],
  q:"이 장면에서 '없는 것'을 두 가지 찾고(힌트: 감정 어휘, Elizabeth의 이름), 그 부재가 수행하는 풍자를 설명해보기.",
  models:[
   {lens:"structure",
    p:"The proposal's comedy is architectural before it is verbal: Austen builds it as a numbered list.",
    e:"Collins marries for reasons \"first\", \"secondly\" and \"thirdly\" — and love appears nowhere on the agenda.",
    t:"The controlling device is bathos through structure: report format imposed on a romantic genre.",
    a:"A list implies items are interchangeable and complete; by numbering his motives, Collins unknowingly certifies that a wife is one more requisition, rankable below his patroness's advice. The absence is load-bearing — Austen does not need to state that he feels nothing, because the form has already confessed it. What the scene satirizes is therefore not one fool but a marriage market in which his paperwork is, technically, in order.",
    l:"The structure answers the question before Elizabeth can: this is not a proposal but an inventory.",
    ko:"구조 렌즈의 핵심 기술 — '형식이 먼저 자백한다'. '없는 것(부재)'을 증거로 쓰는 법도 여기서 연습."},
   {lens:"dialogue",
    p:"Collins's sentences convict him: their sheer length is his character.",
    e:"He cannot say \"I admire you\" without detouring through \"the very noble lady whom I have the honour of calling patroness\".",
    t:"This is self-exposure through register — pompous formality doing the work of description.",
    a:"Every subordinate clause is a small genuflection; the syntax keeps kneeling even when the content stands. Crucially, he is the only one fooled: Elizabeth, the reader and the narrator share the joke, a triangle of dramatic irony with Collins at its blind apex. When he then declines to hear her refusal, the comedy darkens — a speech style that cannot stop talking is also one that cannot listen.",
    l:"Austen needs no narrator's verdict; she simply lets him speak, and the prose style is the character assassination.",
    ko:"대화 렌즈: '문장의 길이·격식 자체가 성격'이라는 명제 + 마지막에 코미디가 어두워지는 지점(거절 무시)까지 — 톤 전환을 잡으면 고득점."}
  ],
  drill:"reader 렌즈로: 'We laugh at Collins, until ...'로 시작해, 웃음이 불편함으로 바뀌는 지점을 짚는 P 한 문장."},

 {id:"s4", sp:36, t:"Wickham의 이야기 — 매력은 증거가 아니다", ch:"Ch.16",
  set:"처음 만난 자리에서 Darcy의 '비밀'을 털어놓는 남자. 독자도 Elizabeth와 함께 속는다.",
  quotes:[
   {en:"\"I have known him too long and too well to be a fair judge. It is impossible for me to be impartial.\" — FALSE MODESTY: 공정할 수 없다고 선언한 뒤 가장 불공정한 진술을 시작한다 — 겸손의 가면을 쓴 공격.", ko:"unreliable testimony 분석의 출발 인용"},
   {en:"\"...till I can forget his father, I can never defy or expose him.\" — DRAMATIC IRONY(재독 시): 폭로하지 않겠다며 지금 폭로하는 중 — 말과 행위의 즉각적 모순.", ko:"재독자만 보이는 층위를 답안에 쓰면 '소설 전체 이해' 점수"},
   {en:"Elizabeth \"honoured him for such feelings, and thought him handsomer than ever as he expressed them.\" — FID + IRONY: 서술이 그녀의 감탄을 그대로 받아 적는다 — 논평 없는 보고가 곧 경고등.", ko:"free indirect discourse 실전 예시. '서술자의 침묵'을 증거로 쓰는 연습"}
  ],
  q:"낯선 사람에게 첫 만남에 비밀을 다 푸는 행위 자체가 보내는 신호는? 'discretion(분별)'이라는 개념으로 분석해보기.",
  models:[
   {lens:"reader",
    p:"First-time readers share Elizabeth's error; re-readers watch her make it — and the novel is built for both audiences at once.",
    e:"As Wickham performs reluctance (\"impossible for me to be impartial\") while attacking Darcy at length, the narration reports that Elizabeth \"thought him handsomer than ever\".",
    t:"The mechanism is restricted perspective fused with free indirect discourse.",
    a:"Because we receive the scene through Elizabeth's admiring filter, his charm is allowed to do to us what it does to her; the narrator offers no warning, and that silence is the trap. On re-reading, every gallant sentence curdles into technique — the same words, a different man. Austen thus makes the reader perform the novel's lesson instead of merely receiving it: we, too, mistook manner for matter.",
    l:"The scene's deepest irony is aimed outward — at us.",
    ko:"독자 렌즈의 최고급 기술: '첫 독자/재독자'의 이중 구도. '서술자의 침묵이 함정'이라는 한 줄은 어느 작품에든 이식 가능."}
  ],
